I've  got to run. If you want to try the test sometime, this is what the   results mean: A high score in Stimulation suggests that you are a smoker   who is stimulated by the cigarette — you feel that it helps wake you,   organize your thoughts, and keep you going.A high score in Handling suggests that you feel satisfied by handling cigarettes.A high score in Pleasure Relaxation suggests that using cigarettes makes you feel good.A high score in Crutch: Tension Reduction suggests you use cigarettes as a crutch in moments of stress or discomfort.A   high score in Craving: Psychological Addiction suggests you are   psychologically addicted to cigarettes. Quitting smoking is difficult   for the person who is psychologically addicted.A high score in Habit suggests that you no longer getting much satisfaction from cigarettes.

Hi 10029. You smoke to reduce your stress. That's a reason a lot of smokers mention. I am curious: And what do you not like about smoking?

What I don't like about smoking. Is the fact I have to go outside. The  knowing fact that I'm shorting my life every time I light up. The fact I might die before I'm able to see my daughter get married, the smell, the taste, the prices.

So you are saying that your health initially gets worse when you are trying to quit?
Yeah. Like. The cigarettes are helping me from dying.
Ok, I see. Do these immediate health effects keep you from trying to quit?

In any case: It's actually quite normal that your body would initially react with some symptoms of sickness. Your lung for example is trying to get rid of all the tar and toxins. Does knowing this change anything for you?

the boyfriend i just got out of a relationship with in november belittled it. he said he quit marijuana, so i definitely quit smoking. and that was a hard time for me; i wasn't ready and he was stressing me out so it never worked. i would just smoke behind his back. i'm not a liar or anything like that when i'm in a relationship, but he was overbearing, which is why it didn't work out. he thought it was easy to quit, but weed doesn't have nearly the amount of addictive qualities as a cig does. and my family is known for having addictive personalities. so its that much harder.... he was a jerk about it. it hurt to know i would have to go through it alone even if he was making me.

just 1 per week

Those are good strategies 10050! If you also need something to replace the oral aspect of a cigarette/cigarillo I can recommend sugarfree gum or hard candy, vegetable sticks, or just a straw or toothpick.

Big Tobacco is advertising E-Cigarettes as a safer and better way to smoke, but studies have shown that they still contain toxins, even without the smoke. Why do you think so many people who smoke are ready to adopt new products even before proper research on their safety has happened? #beingconscious http://tobaccocontrol.bmj.com/content/early/2013/03/05/tobaccocontrol-2012-050859.abstract?papetoc
To keep up with society. To be with the in crowd. I heard those were actually worse

Well with regard to the example you provided, e-cigarettes, it isn't just a matter of people who smoke being willing to try it before their is research on it. People, in general, are willing to try them because it makes sense that they would be safe, as it is essentially just glycerol, nicotine, and water vapor, which they basically are(up to 450 times safer than cigarettes). While not a harmless product, I can't imagine people not willing to try them before research has been done on them. Nobody waits to read the research on their toilet paper brand before trying it. That's because it is rational to assume it is safe enough to use without serious harm.
Cause people are stupid. End of story.

Not on a lot of things, but we enjoy each other's company, and we have other things in common
Do you ever have to hide smoking? How does that affect you? #balance
Nope.
I hide it from whoever I date for awhile. I guess I'm a little ashamed, or I don't want them to judge me from appearance
I used to, but I am very open about it now that I am eighteen.
Is there someone in your life that you'd be proud to tell you quit smoking? What do you think they would say? #smokingaffectsall
My daughter.
My mom
Tell us how your life would be different if your first impression was never smoky? #balance
My friends' parents wouldn't think I'm some street ruffian.
I agree. Same thing
My ex gfs parents didn't like me cause I smoked. So we broke up lol.

Most people who smoke report their top reason for smoking is to deal with stress: work, class, family, friends, significant others- it can be a lot! So can you think of another way you could deal with stress that won’t force you into lighting up when things get tough? What could you do instead? #balance
Smoke some weed. :)
Talking with friends and family ^_^
How could you have a more active lifestyle without smoking? #balance
Smoking caused me to lose a chance for a free scholarship to any college i wanted for football. :(
I could probably start working out again, which I stopped doing around the time I started smoking a lot.
10029 I'm very sorry to hear that! :( 10048, yes that could have been a big factor!- Victoria from TSP
Happy New Year, everyone!!- Victoria from TSP
Post your wish list here!  #balance

Yesterday we asked you to tell us how confident you were that you COULD quit smoking if you wanted to. What would it take to get you from the number you said yesterday to ONE NUMBER HIGHER? #motivation
If I had even less money than I do now. If my cough had blood in it. If my friends quit. A few things could do the trick ^_^
If my friends quit! If my dad quit, too
If my aunt quit.
We understand that stopping smoking is not easy. On a scale of 1-10, how confident are you that you COULD quit smoking if you tried? #motivation
I'd say if I was to quit right now. I would say. 2.
If I had to quit now, I'd say there's a 50% chance I could stick with it
Not very, maybe 3?
Many people associate the beginning of a new year with change. Do you guys have any resolutions for the New Year? #TDII
I've got to run guys - Happy new year everyone and I look forward to working with you in 2015!
Quick question. When do we get our first gift card?
I'm sorry that I haven't responded to this yet! You should get your first gift card after you've fully entered our study and then after 3, 6, 9, and 12 months- Victoria from TSP
What is keeping quitting smoking from the top of your priorities list? What would make quitting even more important to you? #motivation
My image I guess, plus it helps my school work and creativity. I just don't think it's important to quit yet
I guess. Stress. When I make to the top. And reached my life goal. That's when I'll feel I'm ready to quit smoking.
If I spent more money on it than my other bad habits, it would be more important

data.description: I'll be doing another session Q&A this week. Looking forward to seeing you there!

data.message: On a scale of 1-10, how important is it to you to quit smoking for good? #motivation
6. I mainly started to get my parents to quit. It didn't work
Do you think you will ever want to quit smoking? When? #motivation
Whenever i have a reason to
Maybe when it starts to take a greater toll on my health
Yeah.... I could quit if I wanted to but I enjoy what it does to my image. It makes me seem cool
How would you react if you found out your son or daughter smoked cigarettes?  #motivation
I'm not sure. I imagine if I ever have kids, they probably will because I do, and I wouldn't like it but I would understand and not be judgmental about it .
I would do the same thing I did. Forced to eat a cigarette.
It'd be hypocritical to be disappointed
I guess I would quit for them and myself. Set an example
It does change a person's perspective when a child you're responsible for is in the picture. Thanks for sharing, everyone!- Victoria from TSP
What’s the worst thing that could happen if you don’t quit smoking? #motivation
Man. Just thinking about it.... I'd die before I'm able to see my daughter get married.
Getting lung cancer, and having my family go into debt paying for my medical bills while I die.
Cancver
Losing my voice, because I'm a singer
I know it's scary to think about, but we do have to realize the risk and worst case scenario when smoking. Thank you all for being open- Victoria from TSP
What would be the best-case scenario if you quit smoking? #motivation
I do it on my own terms
And I was getting paid to stop haha
Same as 10050. If I was getting paid. And also if murdering became legal just for me.
I have a lighter course load/no stress, and no urges to smoke.
To not smoke anymore?
That's what it'd do for  me
When you are ready is best
What was your reason for picking up that first cigarette? Was it to be cool and independent, to experiment, to look older, something else? #beingconscious

I never wanted to smoke cigarettes, because I was afraid of them(cancer? yikes!), but then I smoked my first when I was drunk and on a few other things. I enjoyed it, smoked more when I was drunk, then I started smoking after I would smoke cannabis, and pretty soon I was just smoking cigs whenever.
Started smoking because my friends did honestly
Cause I was pissed off and I needed something to calm my nerves!!
When I first picked up a cigarette. Was because. I was so extremely stressed and I seen a cig butt. And smoked it.

Thanks for commenting, everyone! Totally understandable that a person is more likely to smoke when surrounded by people who do OR is just exposed to cigarettes. Emotional reasons are totally valid too, I know stress and anger can be really hard to deal with!- Victoria from TSP
Hi everyone and welcome to TSP! I am available for the next hour. Let me know if you have any questions! #TDII
What health concerns would you say there are for nasal snuff users?

Good question 10048! While the hazardous health consequences of smokeless tobacco are lower than smoking cigarettes, smokeless tobacco is not safe or healthy by any means. Tobacco contains carcinogens, there is always the issue of addiction (nicotine), and cardiovascular disease to name a few. More comprehensive information is on the website of the Mayo Clinic. http://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-living/quit-smoking/in-depth/chewing-tobacco/art-20047428?pg=2 What do you think about these? More or less severe than you expected?

Well, it says about what I expected, though I am curious as to how frequently and how severe these health problems occur/are in comparison to smoking. While they aren't a safe alternative to cigarettes, are they safer than cigarettes? I'm interested in the statistics pertaining to deaths caused by the product.

They are definitely safer, there is no denying that. The only good data I know are based on oral snus use in Sweden. There, smoking rates and deaths attributed to smoking are down compared to other countries. Here is some information for you, if you are interested (at least the abstract) http://tobaccocontrol.bmj.com/content/12/4/349.abstract
Thank you so much! This is very useful information.

10048, here is another article on the topic from the British Guardian that contains links to several research studies. Check it out if you are interested and let me know if you have any questions. I am not 100% sure if nasal snuff would be exactly the same in terms of consequences, but I think at least pretty similar. http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/oct/29/sweden-smokers-option-snus
I've got to run guys. Happy Holidays and see you next week!
How would you support someone who tells you they want to quit smoking? #motivation
Give them tips on how to quit and not smoke around them
I would help support someone quitting by not smoking around them and help ease their mind when they're frustrated when they can't smoke a cigarette.
Not offering them smokes, and generally just try to not mention it to them.

data.description: Hi everyone and welcome to the group. Tomorrow, I will be holding the first 'The Doctor Is In' session. You can ask me everything you want to know around smoking, quitting, and the Tobacco Status Project. See you then!

data.message: What are some of your favorite qualities about yourself?  How does smoking fit (or not fit) with that image of you? #balance
One of my favorite qualities about myself is. I'm super chill. I pretty much get along with anybody. But I hate people tho. Which makes smoking fit me. Cause it helps me super chill.
I am independent and can handle being alone. Smoking fits in because I do not take what people see of me very seriously.

My favorite quality is my intellegence(or at least what I perceive to be intelligence ) which is enhanced by nicotine. Tobacco helps me remember things and stay focused. Unfortunately, it makes me appear quite the opposite, at least to others.
My personality:) I think im fun. lol Smoking is just a part sometimes i guess

Smoking is a part of my personality. I seem too far from people. Smoking brings me back down, makes me relatable, real again. Approachable is a better word. I'm so smart, and it intimidates people. But when I whip out a black, it reminds them I'm real. That's how I see it at least
(As in black and mild)
These are all really great qualities, everyone! Another question: whether or not smoking fits with your personality, has it become a part of your identity?- Victoria from TSP

Yes, it definitely has. I feel as though people try to not notice me when I am smoking, like their eyes avoid me. Especially at my residence hall on campus, smoking makes you fit a stereotype and people view it as clique-y.
I guess it has become it. But not a major part, people don't avoid me because I smoke
Share a success that you have had in the past. It can be anything from any time. Why did it work? Who helped? #motivation
The biggest success. Is being a father to my daughter. If it wasn't for my father walking out of my life the way he did. I wouldn't be so motivated and wanting to be part of her life.
That's awesome, 10029! Glad that ended up making such a positive impact on your life. Thanks for sharing!-Victoria from TSP

Related to this,  I quit smoking for two months because my boyfriend hated me smoking. It told him he couldn't smoke weed if I quit smoking. So it helped, but we broke up and I'm smoking again haha. Otherwise, having a planner has always helped achieve things I thought impossible, like working through school or getting assignments done on time. But it takes dedication

Planners are always a good idea, they really work for me! And it's okay if you're smoking again, we're all human. But those two months that you weren't smoking are an achievement too! Dedication all the way :)-Victoria from TSP
I made it across the world! Living a dream I've had for a long time.

I remember one time at a boy scout summer camp, I was the Senior Patrol Leader, and our troop was the only one of all of them troops at the camp who wanted to get some camping award from the camp(ambiguous, but the point is, it was really hard to get, required a lot of extra, random activities, and it was a dense enough list of requirements that all the other troops chose not to attempt it). I had to go to a meeting the night before the completion of the award was due, and I was only able to get a majority of the things finished. So, I explained my predicament to the others, and while I was gone, they finished the rest of the requirements! I was took completely surprised, and the fact that they worked to help get the achievement rather than let me take the whole burden was very refreshing.
That's so great, thank you for sharing, everyone!- Victoria from TSP

Hello everyone! I'm so excited to announce that the group is officially launching today! I will post our first official post in a few minutes; I'm excited to see what you guys think!-Victoria from TSP
Another note: We will be posting one post every day for 90 days! Make sure you all check back and comment/interact with your fellow group members. Don't hesitate to ask questions!
Sweet. When do we start?
Just put up today's post! -Victoria from TSP

This group is for 18-25 year olds who smoke that want to learn more information about tobacco, how it affects your body, and the different quitting options available. Once you get more information about smoking and connect with other young adults who are in the same boat, you can decide if you want to make a change. Getting educated is the first step to making the right decision for YOU. Please engage with our posts and comment every day!
